	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>SADC–EU EPA negotiations on hold as ‘grand FTA’ challenges become apparent</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, SADC–EU EPA negotiations ‘have been shelved with no fixed date for resumption’, with ‘both parties shifting focus to pressing domestic economic and trade issues’. In the case of the SADC this includes the proposed regional tripartite free-trade area (T-FTA), or ‘Grand FTA’, as the proposed agreement of SADC, COMESA and the EAC is commonly referred to.</p><p>At a public trade dialogue meeting in Windhoek in April, trade policy analysts warned that the tripartite FTA would be unlikely to yield substantial benefits if it were based on widespread sector-based exclusions of products from the tariff reduction commitments made. In addition, it was argued that if the new regional trade deal is to deliver real benefits, it will have to address a range of non-tariff barriers to trade. However, the sensitivity of this issue in the agriculture sector was recognised. Trade creation through specialisation was seen as one way of overcoming these sensitivities. A call was made for ‘clear industrial policies on which to base our vision of regional economic integration’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>The Southern Times </i>(Windhoek), ‘EPA negotiations on backburner’, 19 April 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=101916&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a><br />
Inter Press Service, ‘Tripartite free trade plan may repeat previous mistakes’, 26 April 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause_id=1694&amp;news_id=102355&amp;cat_id=1026" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;cause...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Within the T-FTA process, product exclusions and the invocation of special safeguards are likely to be a critical issue in the agricultural sector, where exclusions and safeguards are most commonly invoked. This is a tricky issue in Southern and Eastern Africa, where the economic power of South Africa and Kenya respectively is matter of concern to their neighbours. How in regional trade agreements can the level of product-specific exclusions be minimised, while taking into account the regional complexities which can leave markets functioning in ways which are to the detriment of producers in less developed economies?</p><p>This is a critical policy challenge which will require in-depth consideration and analysis from government policy-makers and concerned private-sector operators. Within SACU it has been agreed that the T-FTA process has to be driven by the member states, and in this context texts prepared by the regional secretariats are seen as inputs to the process, but not the starting point for negotiations, which must remain member-state driven. SACU wants to see market access at least as good as that accorded to the EU under various EPAs, but is willing to use its market access offer to SADC members as the starting point for developing a final offer to T-FTA members. SACU ministers also believe that in future trade-related issues should be addressed, but that work on infrastructure and business visas should be placed on a separate track.</p><p>Similar processes of internal consultations are under way in the EAC and COMESA. There is thus a substantial process of negotiations which needs to be undertaken if the T-FTA process is to progress.</p>
		</div>
		
